Put two large #saucepans{} of water, each with a generous pinch of @salt{generous pinch}, on
to boil for the potatoes and beans. Cut the @new potatoes{2} into quarters (no need to
peel!) and pop them in one of your pans of boiling water. Cook for ~{12-17%minutes}.

> The potatoes are cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Trim the tops from the @green beans{2}. Pick the @tarragon{1/2}(leaf picked and finely chopped,
stalks discarded) leaves from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks).

Pat the @tilapia fillets{4} dry with #kitchen paper{}. Season the fish with a pinch of
@salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Put a splash of @oil{splash} in a #frying pan{} on
medium-high heat. Once the pan is hot, add the fish, skin-side down. Fry for
~{4-5%minutes}. Then, carefully turn and cook for ~{2-3%minutes} more.

> The fish is cooked when the centre is opaque.

Remove it from the pan, set aside and cover with #foil{} to keep warm. Keep the pan -
we'll use it again!

While the fish cooks, pop the green beans in your second pan of boiling water. Cook for
~{4%minutes}, then drain in a #colander{} and put to one side. Boil your #kettle{},
then pour the @water{300%ml} into a #measuring jug{} with the @vegetable stock pot{1}.
Stir to dissolve, ready for the tarragon sauce.

Once your tilapia is out of your frying pan, add the stock to your #pan{} on medium-high
heat. Boil until it has reduced by one third, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove from the heat, then
add the @crème fraîche{1}. Give it a good stir, then add the tarragon (don't use it all
if you only want a subtle flavour). Taste for seasoning and add salt and black pepper
if necessary.

When the potatoes are cooked, drain in your colander and allow to steam-dry for
~{1%minute} (you want as much water to drain out as possible). Return them to the pan
and lightly crush with the back of a #fork{}. For a decadent finish, toss them in a knob
of @?butter{knob} and a pinch of salt and black pepper.

Divide the crushed new potatoes and green beans between your plates. Top with the
tilapia and finish with a generous amount of tarragon sauce. Enjoy!